WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.300 --> 00:00:08.360
- [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:00:09.390 --> 00:00:11.910
This is how we greet people
in my part of the world.

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:15.450
And it means peace
be upon you all.

00:00:15.450 --> 00:00:18.630
Two days ago, Judy
invited us for dinner

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:22.020
at her home, us and all
the rest of the Fellows.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:25.080
And she shared with
us photos and memories

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:28.200
from her grandparents' and her
husband's grandparents' exodus

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:31.860
from Europe after World War II.

00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:34.149
The stories that she
shared reminded me--

00:00:34.149 --> 00:00:35.940
the stories of displacement
that she shared

00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:38.610
reminded me-- of my own
father's displacement

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:40.230
and his own stories.

00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:42.660
We actually-- the
Dajani family--

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:45.170
comes from Jerusalem
and Palestine.

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:47.700
We've been there for
at least 500 years.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:50.100
And this is the tombstone
of one of my ancestors,

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:53.320
who was born in 1459.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:55.570
And that's a shield of
armor for our family.

00:00:55.570 --> 00:01:01.350
And that's a group photo of the
extended family back in 1940s.

00:01:01.350 --> 00:01:03.540
And this is our compound,
the Dajani compound.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.190
We were the ancient--

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:09.450
we're the caretakers of one of
the ancient gates of Jerusalem

00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:11.100
from the ancient city.

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:14.700
But unfortunately,
in 1948, Zionists

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.620
took over my family home.

00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:21.246
And my father and his family had
to flee to Lebanon at that time

00:01:21.246 --> 00:01:22.620
and haven't been
able to go back.

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:25.734
They carry with them the photos,
the keys for their homes.

00:01:25.734 --> 00:01:26.650
And they're not alone.

00:01:26.650 --> 00:01:29.160
There were only 700,000
people who flee then.

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:33.840
So I felt so much compatibility
with Judy's story.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:37.780
And it made me reflect
on displacement

00:01:37.780 --> 00:01:38.980
and what does it mean to us.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:41.160
And I think that
feeling of displacement,

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:45.220
it pushes me to explore,
what does belonging mean?

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:47.610
And I think through a
different series of events,

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:50.190
it's what ended with me
here today in front of you,

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:53.730
to share my journey
and my story.

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:56.100
And not to spare you
anything from Jerusalem,

00:01:56.100 --> 00:01:59.910
I brought with me
today some sweets.

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:02.280
So this is a shop, a sweet
shop that was established

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:03.960
in Jerusalem in the 1860s.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:05.310
It's called Zalatimo.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:08.250
Luckily, they opened a shop
in Jordan, so I was in Jordan

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:09.610
and I brought them with me.

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:13.880
So I hope you'll enjoy
them after the talk.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:16.960
So my talk is
entitled Five Scarves.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:19.330
And I say five scarves,
what I mean is five hats.

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:22.660
You know, the metaphor, you wear
a hat, you wear multiple hats.

00:02:22.660 --> 00:02:25.720
You have different
careers or different roles

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:26.759
you play in life.

00:02:26.759 --> 00:02:28.300
So I don't wear
hats, I wear a scarf.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:30.580
So that's why I'm going to
tell you the five scarves I

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:32.890
wear as I go through my talk.

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:34.880
My talk is divided
into three parts.

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:37.450
Part one will be how the
starred story started.

00:02:37.450 --> 00:02:39.490
Part two, the main
theme of the book.

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:41.680
And then part three,
the unanswered questions

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:47.000
that I hope you will help
me answer during our Q&amp;A.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.600
As human beings,
we enjoy stories.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:52.060
We love to listen to stories.

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:54.400
And I think this is
part of our evolution.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.220
So through ancient
history, as humans evolved,

00:02:57.220 --> 00:02:59.360
probably there were
two groups of people.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.540
A group of people
that sat around

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:04.000
the fire and read
stories, and another

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.822
did not sit around
telling stories.

00:03:06.822 --> 00:03:07.780
They were more serious.

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:10.990
And they frowned upon those
who sat around reading stories.

00:03:10.990 --> 00:03:14.110
And you can imagine which one
of those groups survived today.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:15.380
It's the storytellers.

00:03:15.380 --> 00:03:18.340
So apparently, storytelling
is essential for our survival

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:20.260
as a species to cope
with this world.

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:22.660
So in the spirit
of evolution, I'm

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:26.470
going to share with you my
story and how it brought me here

00:03:26.470 --> 00:03:28.270
to Radcliffe.

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:32.470
So my journey starts
four decades ago.

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:36.610
I come from a family of eight
girls and I'm the eldest.

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:39.940
And we had a boy in the end,
but there's a 20 year difference

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:42.460
between him and I. So I
don't consider he's part

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:45.700
of the family at this point.

00:03:45.700 --> 00:03:49.060
We grew up, there
was no TV by choice.

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:50.020
And so, we read a lot.

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:52.120
We read different
stories and novels.

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:54.880
And we read National Geographic
and Scientific American.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:57.365
And we actually did a
lot of play rolling--

00:03:57.365 --> 00:03:59.980
role playing, to the
extent that sometimes we

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:01.600
mistook the book for real life.

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:02.530
Many, many times.

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:04.560
We're eight girls,
different ages, sizes.

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:06.200
So we could do that.

00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:08.740
And we also had many
debates and discussions

00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:11.620
at home, between us-- the
girls-- and with my parents,

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:13.000
both my mother and father.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.779
And this is what fostered in
us curiosity, asking questions,

00:04:16.779 --> 00:04:19.360
and not letting ourselves to
be comfortable with anything

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:22.609
that was not less than logical
in the way we approach things.

00:04:22.609 --> 00:04:24.400
I also learned three
lessons in that period

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:27.460
of my life, which stemmed from
my upbringing, my culture,

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:28.540
and my religion.

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:31.600
And those were one, that
you have a responsibility

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:32.617
towards your community.

00:04:32.617 --> 00:04:34.450
You have to do something
for your community.

00:04:34.450 --> 00:04:37.150
You can't just enjoy
life by yourself.

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:40.317
And the second lesson
is that we have to-- we

00:04:40.317 --> 00:04:42.400
are responsible for our
time, to do something good

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:42.983
with our time.

00:04:42.983 --> 00:04:45.010
And not to spend
it without meaning.

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:48.110
The third lesson was, it
doesn't matter if you succeed.

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:50.050
What matters is that you try.

00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:51.370
That's the important thing.

00:04:51.370 --> 00:04:54.220
So those lessons are what I
carried along with me in life

00:04:54.220 --> 00:04:57.550
and helped me in what
I did eventually.

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:00.070
Now, in Jordan, if your
father is a physician,

00:05:00.070 --> 00:05:01.210
you go and study medicine.

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:02.200
It's expected of you.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:05.180
And I think, to a certain
extent, it is in many cultures.

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:07.330
So my father was a
physician, and therefore, I

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:09.310
was going to study medicine.

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:12.430
After I went into my
first year at college,

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:16.220
I decided I don't want to do
medicine, because I was scared.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.887
I was scared of making a mistake
and killing someone by mistake.

00:05:18.887 --> 00:05:20.261
And so, I thought,
you know what?

00:05:20.261 --> 00:05:22.125
I'm going to be a
biologist, a scientist.

00:05:22.125 --> 00:05:26.230
And if I make a mistake it will
be with mice or worms or flies.

00:05:26.230 --> 00:05:28.780
And I could sleep if I
made a mistake with them.

00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:30.850
And even as a
scientist, I could still

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:32.690
serve humanity
through my research,

00:05:32.690 --> 00:05:34.900
through discovering the
reasons behind disease,

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:38.410
how proteins communicate,
how cells talk to each other.

00:05:38.410 --> 00:05:41.650
So I studied biology and I
wanted to be a scientist.

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:44.710
Now, when you choose to study
something because you love it,

00:05:44.710 --> 00:05:47.680
you excel in it, and
work becomes play.

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.170
Einstein said, choose
the easiest path.

00:05:50.170 --> 00:05:53.170
That way you enjoy every day
and every day is a play day.

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:55.030
And actually I chose
biology because to me,

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:55.900
it was the easiest.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:56.890
And I love it.

00:05:56.890 --> 00:05:58.600
And to me, everyday
is a play day.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:02.140
I don't consider
my work as work.

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:05.980
I also graduated from college
and then I went and did

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:06.610
my master's.

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:11.330
But in Jordan, there's no PhD
programs back in the 1980s.

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:13.180
And so, there was
no internet, either.

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:14.830
So if you wanted
to study abroad,

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:16.480
you'd have to send a letter
and wait for three weeks

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:18.521
and send another letter
and wait for three weeks.

00:06:18.521 --> 00:06:21.010
And you didn't know what were
the ranges of scholarships

00:06:21.010 --> 00:06:22.750
available.

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:26.102
So I was not able to go, because
I didn't get a scholarship.

00:06:26.102 --> 00:06:28.060
I actually got accepted
at Cambridge University

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:31.390
eventually, but I didn't
have the financial money

00:06:31.390 --> 00:06:32.920
to actually go there.

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:35.020
And by then, I was married
and I had one child.

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:37.750
And my advisor then at
Cambridge University told me,

00:06:37.750 --> 00:06:41.050
you can't come and do
your PhD with one child.

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:44.560
Later on, I did it with
four, but he doesn't know.

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:48.160
So the first scarf that I
like to say proudly I wear

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.520
is the one that I am a
mother of four children.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:52.210
And so, I like to
wear my scarf that I'm

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:53.590
the mother of four children.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:55.131
Now, they're all
grown up, of course.

00:06:55.131 --> 00:06:57.120
This is a picture
a long time ago.

00:06:57.120 --> 00:07:00.160
Now, meanwhile, since I
couldn't become a scientist,

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:01.120
I became a teacher.

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:02.680
So everybody who studies
science in Jordan,

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:04.500
if you're not academic,
you become a teacher.

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:05.833
So I was a teacher for 10 years.

00:07:05.833 --> 00:07:08.710
And I taught elementary school,
high school, from grade 1

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:11.620
to grade 12, I taught biology,
science in English and Arabic.

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.260
All different types of programs.

00:07:13.260 --> 00:07:15.234
And I think that
period of my life

00:07:15.234 --> 00:07:17.650
helped me understand what are
the challenges that children

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:19.229
face in their everyday lives.

00:07:19.229 --> 00:07:20.770
What are the challenges
that teachers

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:23.360
face in their everyday life.

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:25.240
And how important the
job of the teacher.

00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:28.930
And how we, as a community,
don't give enough importance

00:07:28.930 --> 00:07:29.890
for the teacher.

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:33.281
And I always say if I ever
become a minister of education,

00:07:33.281 --> 00:07:34.780
the first thing I
will do is to make

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:38.090
it compulsory for every college
graduate to teach for one year.

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:41.260
It's like military obligation.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:42.290
You have to do that.

00:07:42.290 --> 00:07:43.831
And the reason is
if they do it, they

00:07:43.831 --> 00:07:45.830
realize how difficult
and important

00:07:45.830 --> 00:07:47.780
is the job and the
role of the teacher,

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:51.150
because he or she are bringing
up the next generation.

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:53.930
Well, as I was
teaching, my husband

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.480
saw an ad in the newspaper
that the Fulbright

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:58.241
was offering PhD programs.

00:07:58.241 --> 00:07:59.990
And so he said, Rana,
there's your chance.

00:07:59.990 --> 00:08:02.060
Because my dream is
still to be a scientist.

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:05.920
So I actually, at the age of
30, took my exams all over again

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:07.730
and wrote essays all over again.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:10.610
And I was called for
an interview the day

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:13.850
before my last daughter was due.

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:16.040
And I told them, but
tomorrow's my due date.

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:18.500
And they said, oh,
if you have the baby,

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:22.102
you can call us from
your hospital bed.

00:08:22.102 --> 00:08:23.060
I didn't have the baby.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:25.018
And the baby is actually
sitting here in front,

00:08:25.018 --> 00:08:27.080
[? Zara, ?] she's my last one.

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:28.790
And I went to the interview.

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:31.940
I made the interview,
I got a scholarship.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:33.740
And now, the decision
was, what do we do?

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:38.240
This is a family, a full
family of four kids from zero

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:40.401
to 10 years old.

00:08:40.401 --> 00:08:41.900
And we were thinking,
what do we do?

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:43.070
Do I take the kids and go?

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:45.560
Does my husband keep the kids
in Jordan, I go by myself?

00:08:45.560 --> 00:08:48.080
This is a PhD in
molecular biology,

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.910
it's a five year commitment.

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:51.380
And at that point
my husband, who

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:54.717
was a Lieutenant Colonel in
the Air Force, he said, Rana,

00:08:54.717 --> 00:08:55.550
I'm going to resign.

00:08:55.550 --> 00:08:58.220
So he resigned so that we could
keep the whole family together.

00:08:58.220 --> 00:09:00.207
And we went as one
unit to the US,

00:09:00.207 --> 00:09:01.790
so that we could
take care of the kids

00:09:01.790 --> 00:09:03.230
together, make
sure that they had

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:06.600
a healthy home with both parents
there to take care of them.

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:09.440
So my husband has been
my mentor and my friend

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:12.400
and supporting me in
everything I do all along.

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:14.270
So I moved to the states.

00:09:14.270 --> 00:09:16.580
First of all, I made it
very clear to my advisor

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.370
that my family is as
important as my research.

00:09:19.370 --> 00:09:22.830
And if push comes to
shove, my kids come first.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:25.430
So I always left at five, I
never came in on weekends.

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:28.160
And yet, I graduated
similar to my peers who

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:29.750
didn't have kids,
who were single,

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:32.280
who stayed all night in
the lab and on weekends.

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.670
So it's about time
management, knowing

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.650
how to do things
in the right way,

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:38.570
and setting your
priorities right.

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:41.035
And at home, actually my kids--

00:09:41.035 --> 00:09:41.660
I trained them.

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:43.190
They did all the chores.

00:09:43.190 --> 00:09:45.020
They did all the dinners.

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:47.090
Many times, if I had an
exam, I would come home

00:09:47.090 --> 00:09:50.900
to find a six course dinner done
by my son, not my daughters.

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:54.110
Or a pie coming out of the
oven, very hot because I

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:55.820
had an exam or something.

00:09:55.820 --> 00:09:58.560
And not just that, I actually
involved them in my work.

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.500
So every time I'd
go home and share

00:10:00.500 --> 00:10:02.390
my experiments and my
results, and they'd

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:04.020
come up with hypotheses.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:07.260
So when Mama was late, she
was testing their hypotheses.

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:08.600
So they were really excited.

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:11.510
And they made friends
with all my mice.

00:10:11.510 --> 00:10:14.090
And of course, I was not allowed
to kill them until after--

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:18.059
I had to beg them that I had to
do it and I would explain why.

00:10:18.059 --> 00:10:19.850
And actually, they all
have acknowledgments

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:23.120
in my publications for
being part of my research.

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:26.850
But that led to them being
immune to anything scientific.

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:28.687
So none of them went
to science at all.

00:10:28.687 --> 00:10:30.020
They're all into the humanities.

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:32.870
They've had enough growing
up with being a scientist.

00:10:32.870 --> 00:10:35.270
And this is them
celebrating with me.

00:10:35.270 --> 00:10:37.250
They put me this
big card that I just

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:39.080
won a PhD, as if you win it.

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:42.200
You know, it's not
that we worked hard.

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:44.900
So then, after that we,
went back to Jordan.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:49.310
And in Jordan, I started
at the University my work.

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:50.720
At the same time,
when you change

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:52.845
from one country to one
country or from one culture

00:10:52.845 --> 00:10:56.690
to another culture, you
realize that there's

00:10:56.690 --> 00:10:58.200
something different.

00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:01.210
Things that you didn't notice
before you notice again,

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:02.450
either bad or good.

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:05.180
And that's when I noticed that
children in Jordan don't read,

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:06.320
don't read for pleasure.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:09.300
So they read for education, they
read for religious purposes.

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:11.570
But when you speak about
reading for pleasure--

00:11:11.570 --> 00:11:14.090
under the covers, you can't
wait to finish the story--

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:15.139
that kind of reading.

00:11:15.139 --> 00:11:17.180
And that kind of reading
is very, very important,

00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:20.830
because when you
read for pleasure,

00:11:20.830 --> 00:11:23.330
this boosts your
imagination, your creativity.

00:11:23.330 --> 00:11:24.740
You gain vocabulary.

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:26.960
And this vocabulary helps
you express yourself better

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:28.254
and you become less violent.

00:11:28.254 --> 00:11:29.670
You'll learn about
other cultures.

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:32.240
So this develops your empathy
to understand others, listen

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:34.610
to others, and communicate
better with others.

00:11:34.610 --> 00:11:36.792
And you become more
confident, because you

00:11:36.792 --> 00:11:38.750
draw from the heroes you
read about the courage

00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:40.490
to make a difference
in your own life.

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:42.930
So reading for pleasure
is very, very important.

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:45.770
And I was looking in--
especially like in Jordan

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:47.660
and Arab countries--

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:49.540
Islam is the majority religion.

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:52.730
And the first word
of the Quran is read.

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:55.610
So to me, the question is, why
don't we read for pleasure?

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:57.380
And I did some research
and I found out

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:58.610
that the reason we
don't read for pleasure

00:11:58.610 --> 00:11:59.984
is because we
don't love to read.

00:11:59.984 --> 00:12:00.840
There's no passion.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:05.300
There's no-- this burning need
and desire that I want to read.

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:08.330
And also I did some research
to try to understand, how do we

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:09.660
plant that love of reading?

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:11.376
How do we make
people love to read?

00:12:11.376 --> 00:12:13.250
And I found out, although
many people thought

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:15.650
it was because they
don't have enough books,

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:17.670
I found out that was
not the main reason.

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:19.670
The main reason that
children don't love to read

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:21.380
is because their parents
don't read aloud to them

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:22.550
when they're very young.

00:12:22.550 --> 00:12:24.140
You should read to
your child as early

00:12:24.140 --> 00:12:25.973
as when the mother is
pregnant, because what

00:12:25.973 --> 00:12:27.684
happens in the
brain of the child,

00:12:27.684 --> 00:12:29.600
there becomes a connection
between the feeling

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:33.450
of security, happiness,
and comfort with reading.

00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:36.200
So you grow up, you want to be
a reader because it gives you

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:38.540
this good sense, the sense
of happiness, security

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:40.890
that you don't know
where it comes from.

00:12:40.890 --> 00:12:46.450
So I found the solution to
make children love to read.

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:47.860
So what did I do at that time?

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:48.600
I mean, I could--

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:51.194
it's impossible to go around
and tell every parent,

00:12:51.194 --> 00:12:52.860
you have to read aloud
to your children.

00:12:52.860 --> 00:12:53.951
That's too much.

00:12:53.951 --> 00:12:55.950
And even if I told the
government to pass a law,

00:12:55.950 --> 00:12:58.440
that doesn't mean they're
going to follow the law.

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:00.300
So I felt this huge
responsibility.

00:13:00.300 --> 00:13:01.508
And I thought, you know what?

00:13:01.508 --> 00:13:04.260
I'm going to collect together
the children in my neighborhood

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:05.462
and read aloud to them.

00:13:05.462 --> 00:13:06.420
And that's what we did.

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:08.190
It was a family project.

00:13:08.190 --> 00:13:09.840
My husband and
children were involved.

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:11.381
And we started
reading in the mosque,

00:13:11.381 --> 00:13:12.880
because it's in
every neighborhood.

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:13.890
And we thought, why not?

00:13:13.890 --> 00:13:14.430
It's clean.

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:15.270
It's got a carpet.

00:13:15.270 --> 00:13:16.557
It's got a bathroom.

00:13:16.557 --> 00:13:18.390
And the first time we
announced that there's

00:13:18.390 --> 00:13:21.524
going to be a read aloud, the
parents dragged their children

00:13:21.524 --> 00:13:23.940
to come and attend, because
they heard in the announcement

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:26.850
reading, education,
mosque, religion.

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:27.690
This is great.

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:29.640
The children didn't
want to come of course,

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.190
but because we're very
obedient, they all came.

00:13:32.190 --> 00:13:33.620
But when they come, I dress--

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:36.690
I bring funny stories
from their culture,

00:13:36.690 --> 00:13:39.464
from their everyday life
in their native tongue.

00:13:39.464 --> 00:13:41.630
And the children just fell
in love with the stories.

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:43.606
And then they line up
and take the books home.

00:13:43.606 --> 00:13:45.230
And they started
becoming the champions

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:46.760
of reading within
their own homes,

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:48.440
begging their parents
to read to them

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.500
or themselves reading to
their peers or their siblings.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.690
And so, a culture of
reading for pleasure

00:13:53.690 --> 00:13:55.640
started to grow in
my neighborhood.

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:58.490
And the program, we
called it We Love Reading.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:13:59.840
And it began to grow.

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:02.720
So we created a training program
for women, and then later men

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:03.620
as well.

00:14:03.620 --> 00:14:05.810
And we started developing
our own stories

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:07.280
for children in Arabic.

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:10.190
And the program flourished
and spread, as Judy

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:13.490
said, now it's actually
35 countries and counting.

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:15.740
And we base all our
programming on research,

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:17.210
because I'm a scientist.

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:20.490
So we involved Yale
University, Harvard University,

00:14:20.490 --> 00:14:21.960
Chicago University, and Brown.

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:24.890
And we did studies on different
aspects of the program

00:14:24.890 --> 00:14:26.750
to make sure that what
we're doing is right

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:29.060
and how we can develop
it even better.

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:31.550
And I'm going to show you a
short video of We Love Reading

00:14:31.550 --> 00:14:34.460
and how it has spread and has
been so effective, specifically

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:35.840
in refugee contexts.

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:38.600
Where the children are
in need of an education

00:14:38.600 --> 00:14:41.750
program that they can engage
in, even if there is no school.

00:14:41.750 --> 00:14:44.810
And where adults need a purpose
and agency in their lives.

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:47.270
Because in We Love Reading,
adults are all volunteers.

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:48.320
We don't pay them.

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:50.150
And they only do it
not because they do it

00:14:50.150 --> 00:14:51.860
for me or for the
program, they actually

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.041
read aloud to the children
for their own good,

00:14:54.041 --> 00:14:55.040
for their own community.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:56.480
So it's sustainable
in that sense

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:58.990
and gives them
agency and ownership.

00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:00.729
So enjoy.

00:15:00.729 --> 00:15:02.725
